 proof of wide-ranging and large-scale fraud on Wall Street before, during, and after the crisis. The pattern of criminal indulgences exposes the onset of a new degree of crony capitalism in which the most economically and political powerful can commit financial crimes of vast scale with criminal and regulatory immunity. A new economic royalty has seized the commanding heights of our economy through their control of trillions in corporate and individual wealth and their ability to dispense patronage. The Case for the Corporate Death Penalty shows that this new lawlessness poses a profound threat that urgently demands political action and proposes attainable measures to restore the rule of law in the financial sector.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mrz 2024) 0aDerivative securitieszUnited States. 0aFinancial institutionsxCorrupt practiceszUnited States. 0aFinancial institutionsxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aFinancial services industryxGovernment policyzUnited States. 0aGlobal Financial Crisis, 2008-2009. 0aSubprime mortgage loanszUnited States. 7aLAW / Banking.2bisacsh  aCorporate.  aCrime.  aPolicing.  aauthorities.  aeconomics.  afinancial.1 aRamirez, Steven A., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut40uhttps://doi.org/10.18574/nyu/9781479878529.001.000140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781479878529423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781479878529/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LAEC  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LAEC  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_ESTMALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles